== Renjō-ji (璉珹寺) ==

'''Renjō-ji''' (璉珹寺) is a temple of the {{ill|Jōdo Shinshū Kenkyō-in Sect|ja|浄土真宗遣迎院派|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Nara City|ja|奈良市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}, Japan.

== History ==

According to temple records, Renjō-ji was founded during the {{ill|Tenpyō era|ja|天平|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} under the imperial decree of {{ill|Emperor Shōmu|ja|聖武天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} by {{ill|Gyōki|ja|行基|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}. It was later rebuilt in the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} by {{ill|Ki no Aritsune|ja|紀有常|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="kenshi">Iwakiri Takatoshi, Oya Yoshinori, eds., "Nara Prefecture History Vol. 6: Temples," Meicho Shuppan, 1991, p.273.</ref><ref name="shishi">Nara City History Editorial Council, "Nara City History: Temples Edition," Yoshikawa Kōbunkan, 1985, p.125.</ref>

It is also believed to be associated with the remains of {{ill|Ki-dera Temple|ja|紀寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}, evidenced by the discovery of early Nara period tiles in the surrounding area.<ref name="shishi" />

In 1602, {{ill|Tokugawa Ieyasu|ja|徳川家康|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} granted Renjō-ji land worth 20 koku in Chōtsuka and Hokkeji villages, a temple domain maintained throughout the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="kenshi" /><ref name="heibon">"Japanese Historical Place Names Series Vol. 30: Nara Prefecture," Heibonsha, 1981, p.520.</ref>

The temple was initially affiliated with the {{ill|Hossō sect|ja|法相宗|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}, later becoming a sub-temple of {{ill|Seigan-ji|ja|誓願寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Jōdo sect|ja|浄土宗|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}. In 1725, it converted to {{ill|Tendai Buddhism|ja|天台宗|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}, becoming a sub-temple of {{ill|Yōgen-in|ja|養源院|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} in Kyoto.<ref name="shishi" /> Currently, Renjō-ji belongs to the Jōdo Shinshū Kenkyō-in Sect and operates without parishioners.<ref name="shishi" />

Although it experienced decline after the Meiji Restoration, Renjō-ji has since been restored, with an expanded cemetery and maintained temple grounds.<ref name="shishi" /> In 1964, a large {{ill|Kannon|ja|観音|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} statue was erected to honor war casualties.<ref name="shishi" />

== Grounds ==

The temple features a main gate, a kitchen building to the left, and a guest hall beyond the central gate.<ref name="shishi" /> Several stone statues of ancient Buddhas are visible near the central gate and to the right of the main hall.<ref name="shishi" />

The central object of worship is a white, unclothed standing statue of {{ill|Amida Nyorai|ja|阿弥陀如来|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} from the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}, adorned with a fabric hakama. This sacred image is unveiled annually in May.<ref name="shishi" /><ref name="heibon" />

Flanking the main deity are standing statues of {{ill|Kannon Bosatsu|ja|観音菩薩|1=Guanyin|2=ja|3=観音菩薩|lt=Kannon Bodhisattva|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} (Heian period) and {{ill|Seishi Bosatsu|ja|勢至菩薩|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} (Muromachi period), both designated as {{ill|Important Cultural Properties of Japan|ja|重要文化財|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)|2=ja|3=重要文化財|lt=Important Cultural Property|qq= (Japan)|4=ko|5=일본의_중요문화재|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="heibon" /><ref name="shishi" />

== Cultural Properties ==

=== Important Cultural Properties ===

* Wooden Standing Statue of {{ill|Kannon Bosatsu|ja|観音菩薩|1=Guanyin|2=ja|3=観音菩薩|lt=Kannon Bodhisattva|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}
* Wooden Standing Statue of {{ill|Seishi Bosatsu|ja|勢至菩薩|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}

=== Other Cultural Properties ===

* Wooden Standing Statue of {{ill|Amida Nyorai|ja|阿弥陀如来|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} (designated tangible cultural property of Nara Prefecture)

== Related Sites ==

